(58, 1, '2014-02-01 16:28:03', '2014-02-01 15:28:03', '<!--:SR--><h1><span style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.3333333333;">Ratifikacijom Ugovora o osnivanju energetske zajednice između EU i zemalja Jugoistočne Evrope, Republika Srbija je prihvatila obavezu da donese i realizuje plan primene direktive 2001/77/EC i 2003/30/EC o promovisanju proizvodnje električne energije iz obnovljivih izvora i smanjenju emisije gasova koji zagađuju životnu sredinu. Tokom 2009. godine Evropski parlament i Savet Evropske unije usvojili su Direktivu 2009/28/EC o promovisanju upotrebe energije iz obnovljivih izvora i poništili Direktivu 2001/77/EC i 2003/30/EC.</span></h1>\n<div>\n\nŠto se Srbije tiče, Radna grupa Energetske zajednice Jugoistočne Evrope usaglasila je da je udeo energije iz obnovljivih izvora u Srbiji u 2009. god. iznosio 21,2% u bruto finalnoj potrošnji energije.\n\nOvo predstavlja osnovu za utvrđivanje udela obnovljivih izvora koji Srbija, u skladu sa evropskim ciljevima, treba da ostvari do 2020. Godine, a koji iznosi 27% bruto finalne potrošnje.\n\nOvo poboljšanje energetske budućnosti je neophodno kako bi Srbija doprinela svetskoj borbi protiv klimatskih promena.\n\nU tom cilju, nadležne institucije u Srbiji ustanovili su regulativu koja bi omogućila investicije u obnovljive izvore energije, između ostalog i vetar. Pogodna regulativa za razvoj projekata obnovljivih izvora energije igra veliku ulogu u privlačenju potrebnih stranih ulaganja i otvaranja radnih mesta u opštinama u kojima su projekti locirani.\n\nZakon o energetici i prateća regulativa prepoznaje značaj obnovljivih izvora energije. Međutim, kako bi se veliki projekti poput vetroelektrana realizovali, neophodno je da se donesu određene izmene samog zakona, a čije donošenje se očekuje krajem 2013. godine.\n\n</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<h5>Usvojen su i četiri bitne Uredbe (podzakonski akti) koje čine osnovu okvira podsticajnih mera za projekte obnovljivih izvora energije:</h5>\n<div>• Uredba o uslovima i postupku sticanja statusa povlašćenog proizvođača električne energije (Sl. glasnik RS, br. 8/2013),\n• Uredba o merama podsticaja za povlašćene proizvođače električne energije (Sl. glasnik RS, br. 8/2013),\n• Uredba o načinu obračuna i načinu raspodele prikupljenih sredstava po osnovu naknade za podsticaj povlašćenih proizvođača električne energije (Sl. glasnik RS, br. 8/2013),\n• Uredba o visini posebne naknade za podsticaj u 2013. godini (Sl. glasnik RS, br. 8/2013).</div>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<h5>Da bi zakonski okvir bio potpuno zatvoren nedostaje odgovarajući Ugovor o otkupu električne energije (PPA), koji je neophodan kako bi se omogućilo finansiranje projekata. Sadašnja verzija ovog ugovora ne zadovoljava zahteve banaka i finansijskih institucija. Usvajanje odgovarajuće verzije Ugovora se očekuje početkom 2014. godine.</h5>\n26. januara 2009. godine Republika Srbija je postala članica i osnivač Međunarodne agencije za obnovljivu energiju (IRENA- International Renewable Energy Agency), kao prve međunarodne organizacije koja se fokusira isključivo na obnovljivu energiju i aktivno će nastaviti učešće u radu ove agencije u skladu sa Statutom Agencije i svojim interesima u oblasti aktiviranja i korišćenja obnovljivih izvora energije.\n\n</div><!--:--><!--:en--><h1>How did it begin - Regulatory rules</h1>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<h5>With the ratification of the Treaty establishing the Energy Community between EU and South East European countries, the Republic of Serbia accepted the obligation to pass and execute the plan of implementation of Directive 2001/77/EC and 2003/30/EC on the promotion of production of electricity from renewable energy sources and reduction of gas emissions polluting the environment. In the course of 2009 the European Parliament and the European Union Council passed the Directive 2009/28/EC on the promotion of the use of energy from renewable sources and repealing of Directives 2001/77/EC and 2003/30/EC.\n\nAs for Serbia, the Task Force of the Energy Community of Southeast Europe determined that the share of energy from renewable sources in Serbia in 2009 makes 21.2% of the gross final energy consumption.\n\nThis served as a basis for determining the share of renewable sources that Serbia is to realize by 2020 in accordance with the European targets, which makes 27% of the gross final consumption.\n\nSuch improvement of the energy future is essential in order for Serbia to contribute to the global struggle against climate changes.\n\nThe competent institutions in Serbia have established for this purpose a subregulation that would enable investments in renewable energy sources, the wind among others. A convenient regulation for the development of renewable energy sources projects plays a major role in attracting the required foreign investments and opening up of jobs in the municipalities in which the projects are situated.\n\nThe Energy Law and the accompanying regulations recognize the importance of renewable energy sources. However, in order to realize the major projects such as wind parks, it is necessary to make certain amendments to the Law, which is expected to be passed by the end of 2013.</h5>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<h5>Four essential Decrees (bylaws) have been passed which form the basis of the framework of incentive measures for the projects of renewable energy sources:</h5>\n<div>• Decree on conditions and procedures for attaining the status of preferential electric power producer (Official Gazette of the Republic of Serbia No. 8/2013),\n• Decree on incentive measures for preferential electric power producers (Official Gazette of the Republic of Serbia No. 8/2013),\n• Decree on the manner of accounting and allocation of collected assets based on remuneration for stimulation of electric power producers (Official Gazette of the Republic of Serbia No. 8/2013),\n• Decree on special remuneration tariffs for incentive in 2013 (Official Gazette of the Republic of Serbia No. 8/2013).</div>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<h5>For a legal framework to be fully complete, a respective Power Purchase Agreement (PPA), which is necessary to facilitate project financing, is missing. The current version of this agreement does not meet the requirements of banks and financial institutions. The adoption of the respective version of the Agreement is expected in early 2014.\n\nOn January 26, 2009 the Republic of Serbia became a member and founder of the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA), as the first international organizations focused solely on renewable energy and will continue active participation in the work of this agency in accordance with the Agency Statute and its interests in the domain of activation and use of renewable energy sources.</h5>\n</div><!--:-->', '<!--:SR-->Kako je sve počelo - zakonska regulativa<!--:--><!--:en-->How did it begin - Regulatory rules<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '26-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-02-01 16:28:03', '2014-02-01 15:28:03', '', 26, 'http://nemanja-pc/?p=58', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(59, 1, '2014-02-01 16:28:25', '2014-02-01 15:28:25', '<!--:SR-->Ratifikacijom Ugovora o osnivanju energetske zajednice između EU i zemalja Jugoistočne Evrope, Republika Srbija je prihvatila obavezu da donese i realizuje plan primene direktive 2001/77/EC i 2003/30/EC o promovisanju proizvodnje električne energije iz obnovljivih izvora i smanjenju emisije gasova koji zagađuju životnu sredinu. Tokom 2009. godine Evropski parlament i Savet Evropske unije usvojili su Direktivu 2009/28/EC o promovisanju upotrebe energije iz obnovljivih izvora i poništili Direktivu 2001/77/EC i 2003/30/EC.\r\n\r\nŠto se Srbije tiče, Radna grupa Energetske zajednice Jugoistočne Evrope usaglasila je da je udeo energije iz obnovljivih izvora u Srbiji u 2009. god. iznosio 21,2% u bruto finalnoj potrošnji energije.\r\n\r\nOvo predstavlja osnovu za utvrđivanje udela obnovljivih izvora koji Srbija, u skladu sa evropskim ciljevima, treba da ostvari do 2020. Godine, a koji iznosi 27% bruto finalne potrošnje.\r\n\r\nOvo poboljšanje energetske budućnosti je neophodno kako bi Srbija doprinela svetskoj borbi protiv klimatskih promena.\r\n\r\nU tom cilju, nadležne institucije u Srbiji ustanovili su regulativu koja bi omogućila investicije u obnovljive izvore energije, između ostalog i vetar. Pogodna regulativa za razvoj projekata obnovljivih izvora energije igra veliku ulogu u privlačenju potrebnih stranih ulaganja i otvaranja radnih mesta u opštinama u kojima su projekti locirani.\r\n\r\nZakon o energetici i prateća regulativa prepoznaje značaj obnovljivih izvora energije. Međutim, kako bi se veliki projekti poput vetroelektrana realizovali, neophodno je da se donesu određene izmene samog zakona, a čije donošenje se očekuje krajem 2013. godine.\r\n\r\nUsvojen su i četiri bitne Uredbe (podzakonski akti) koje čine osnovu okvira podsticajnih mera za projekte obnovljivih izvora energije:\r\n• Uredba o uslovima i postupku sticanja statusa povlašćenog proizvođača električne energije (Sl. glasnik RS, br. 8/2013),\r\n• Uredba o merama podsticaja za povlašćene proizvođače električne energije (Sl. glasnik RS, br. 8/2013),\r\n• Uredba o načinu obračuna i načinu raspodele prikupljenih sredstava po osnovu naknade za podsticaj povlašćenih proizvođača električne energije (Sl. glasnik RS, br. 8/2013),\r\n• Uredba o visini posebne naknade za podsticaj u 2013. godini (Sl. glasnik RS, br. 8/2013).\r\n\r\nDa bi zakonski okvir bio potpuno zatvoren nedostaje odgovarajući Ugovor o otkupu električne energije (PPA), koji je neophodan kako bi se omogućilo finansiranje projekata. Sadašnja verzija ovog ugovora ne zadovoljava zahteve banaka i finansijskih institucija. Usvajanje odgovarajuće verzije Ugovora se očekuje početkom 2014. godine.</h5>\r\n26. januara 2009. godine Republika Srbija je postala članica i osnivač Međunarodne agencije za obnovljivu energiju (IRENA- International Renewable Energy Agency), kao prve međunarodne organizacije koja se fokusira isključivo na obnovljivu energiju i aktivno će nastaviti učešće u radu ove agencije u skladu sa Statutom Agencije i svojim interesima u oblasti aktiviranja i korišćenja obnovljivih izvora energije.\r\n<!--:--><!--:en--><h1>How did it begin - Regulatory rules</h1>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h5>With the ratification of the Treaty establishing the Energy Community between EU and South East European countries, the Republic of Serbia accepted the obligation to pass and execute the plan of implementation of Directive 2001/77/EC and 2003/30/EC on the promotion of production of electricity from renewable energy sources and reduction of gas emissions polluting the environment. In the course of 2009 the European Parliament and the European Union Council passed the Directive 2009/28/EC on the promotion of the use of energy from renewable sources and repealing of Directives 2001/77/EC and 2003/30/EC.\r\n\r\nAs for Serbia, the Task Force of the Energy Community of Southeast Europe determined that the share of energy from renewable sources in Serbia in 2009 makes 21.2% of the gross final energy consumption.\r\n\r\nThis served as a basis for determining the share of renewable sources that Serbia is to realize by 2020 in accordance with the European targets, which makes 27% of the gross final consumption.\r\n\r\nSuch improvement of the energy future is essential in order for Serbia to contribute to the global struggle against climate changes.\r\n\r\nThe competent institutions in Serbia have established for this purpose a subregulation that would enable investments in renewable energy sources, the wind among others. A convenient regulation for the development of renewable energy sources projects plays a major role in attracting the required foreign investments and opening up of jobs in the municipalities in which the projects are situated.\r\n\r\nThe Energy Law and the accompanying regulations recognize the importance of renewable energy sources. However, in order to realize the major projects such as wind parks, it is necessary to make certain amendments to the Law, which is expected to be passed by the end of 2013.</h5>\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h5>Four essential Decrees (bylaws) have been passed which form the basis of the framework of incentive measures for the projects of renewable energy sources:</h5>\r\n<div>• Decree on conditions and procedures for attaining the status of preferential electric power producer (Official Gazette of the Republic of Serbia No. 8/2013),\r\n• Decree on incentive measures for preferential electric power producers (Official Gazette of the Republic of Serbia No. 8/2013),\r\n• Decree on the manner of accounting and allocation of collected assets based on remuneration for stimulation of electric power producers (Official Gazette of the Republic of Serbia No. 8/2013),\r\n• Decree on special remuneration tariffs for incentive in 2013 (Official Gazette of the Republic of Serbia No. 8/2013).</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h5>For a legal framework to be fully complete, a respective Power Purchase Agreement (PPA), which is necessary to facilitate project financing, is missing. The current version of this agreement does not meet the requirements of banks and financial institutions. The adoption of the respective version of the Agreement is expected in early 2014.\r\n\r\nOn January 26, 2009 the Republic of Serbia became a member and founder of the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA), as the first international organizations focused solely on renewable energy and will continue active participation in the work of this agency in accordance with the Agency Statute and its interests in the domain of activation and use of renewable energy sources.</h5>\r\n</div><!--:-->', '<!--:SR-->Kako je sve počelo - zakonska regulativa<!--:--><!--:en-->How did it begin - Regulatory rules<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '26-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-01 16:28:25', '2014-02-01 15:28:25', '', 26, 'http://nemanja-pc/?p=59', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
